---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Container from "../components/Container.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";

const title = "Security — InferBridge";
const description =
  "How InferBridge handles key encryption, API authentication, data residency, and the content-never-logged invariant.";
const canonical = "https://www.inferbridge.dev/security";
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical}>
  <main class="page">
    <Container>
      <header class="masthead">
        <a class="back" href="/">← Back to home</a>
      </header>

      <article class="doc">
        <header class="doc-header">
          <h1>Security</h1>
          <p class="lede">{description}</p>
        </header>

        <section class="prose" aria-labelledby="byok">
          <h2 id="byok">Bring Your Own Keys</h2>
          <p>
            InferBridge never stores your provider API keys in plaintext.
            All BYOK keys are encrypted at rest using <strong>Fernet</strong>
            symmetric encryption (AES-128-CBC with HMAC-SHA256 for
            authentication) before being written to the database.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Fernet key itself is validated at server boot. If
            <code>INFERBRIDGE_ENCRYPTION_KEY</code> is missing or malformed,
            startup hard-fails with a <code>RuntimeError</code> rather than
            running with broken crypto.
          </p>
          <p>
            Provider keys are never returned in API responses.
            <code>GET /v1/keys</code> returns key metadata
            (<code>id</code>, <code>provider</code>, <code>residency</code>,
            <code>declared_region</code>, <code>label</code>,
            <code>created_at</code>) but the secret itself is excluded from
            the response shape entirely.
          </p>
          <p>
            Keys are decrypted in memory only at request time, used for the
            single upstream provider call, and immediately discarded when
            the request completes.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="prose" aria-labelledby="api-auth">
          <h2 id="api-auth">API Key Authentication</h2>
          <p>
            InferBridge API keys (<code>ib_</code> prefix) are stored as
            <strong>SHA-256 hashes</strong>, not in plaintext. The raw secret
            is 32 base62 characters, giving roughly 190 bits of entropy.
          </p>
          <p>
            SHA-256 is appropriate for this use case. Unlike user passwords,
            machine-generated tokens with this much entropy gain no
            additional security from a slow-hashing function like bcrypt or
            Argon2 — those defend against guessing low-entropy inputs, which
            isn't the threat model here.
          </p>
          <p>
            Key comparison uses <code>hmac.compare_digest</code> to defeat
            timing side-channels, even though the entropy already makes a
            timing attack impractical.
          </p>
          <p>
            Keys are shown once at creation and never again. If you lose a
            key, register a new user; we cannot recover the original.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="prose" aria-labelledby="content-privacy">
          <h2 id="content-privacy">Prompt and Completion Privacy</h2>
          <p>
            InferBridge logs request <em>metadata</em> only: provider, model,
            mode, input/output token counts, cost, latency, status, residency,
            and request ID. Prompt text and completion text are never written
            to logs and never stored in the database.
          </p>
          <p>
            This invariant is enforced by an automated test —
            <code>test_prompts_and_completions_never_reach_log_output</code>
            in <code>tests/test_chat_api.py</code> — that runs on every
            commit. It plants sentinel strings in both the prompt and the
            mocked upstream response, drives a real chat request through the
            FastAPI app, and asserts that neither sentinel appears in any
            captured log record. If any future change leaks content into a
            log line, CI fails.
          </p>
          <p>
            The motivation is DPDP and GDPR compliance: prompts frequently
            contain personal data — names, email addresses, support-ticket
            details, medical context — and treating "log volumes" as a
            regulated dataset is a much larger operational burden than
            simply not capturing the content in the first place.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="prose" aria-labelledby="residency">
          <h2 id="residency">Data Residency</h2>
          <p>
            The InferBridge API runs on Railway in the
            <strong>Mumbai region</strong>. Request metadata logs, encrypted
            BYOK keys, and user records are stored in this region.
          </p>
          <p>
            For inference traffic, the
            <code>X-InferBridge-Residency</code> header restricts routing to
            providers operating in the requested zone. If no provider in a
            tier satisfies the residency constraint, the request fails fast
            with a 422 <code>residency_error</code> rather than silently
            falling back to a provider in another region.
          </p>
          <p>The available residency zones map as follows:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <code>india</code> — Sarvam, Krutrim, and any
              <code>self_hosted</code> endpoint registered with
              <code>declared_region: "india"</code>.
            </li>
            <li>
              <code>eu</code> — Mistral.
            </li>
            <li>
              <code>global</code> — OpenAI, Anthropic, Together, Groq,
              DeepSeek, Cohere.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="prose" aria-labelledby="transport">
          <h2 id="transport">Transport Security</h2>
          <p>
            All InferBridge API endpoints require HTTPS. TLS certificates
            are managed by Railway and renewed automatically via
            Let's Encrypt.
          </p>
          <p>
            For BYOK <code>self_hosted</code> entries, plain HTTP
            <code>base_url</code> values are rejected at registration time
            unless the host is <code>localhost</code> (or
            <code>*.localhost</code>), or resolves to a loopback, private,
            or link-local IP address. This guards against a misconfiguration
            that would route gateway traffic to a plaintext upstream over
            the open internet, while leaving the dev-loop usable when the
            target is something like
            <code>http://localhost:11434</code> for a local Ollama instance.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="prose" aria-labelledby="audit">
          <h2 id="audit">DPDP Audit Export</h2>
          <p>
            <code>GET /v1/audit/export</code> generates a tamper-evident
            report of all request metadata for a given date range, signed
            with SHA-256.
          </p>
          <p>
            The signature is computed over the canonical serialization of
            the report body (sorted keys, no whitespace, signature key
            removed before hashing). A four-line Python verifier in the
            documentation lets auditors re-derive the digest independently,
            without trusting InferBridge or the SDK.
          </p>
          <p>
            Reports can be filtered by residency zone and exported as JSON
            or PDF. Both formats include the same signature, surfaced both
            in the body and in the
            <code>X-InferBridge-Audit-Signature</code> response header so
            it can be archived separately from the body itself. Free-tier
            accounts retain <code>request_logs</code> rows for 30 days;
            export before the window closes for compliance records that
            need to outlive that.
          </p>
          <p>
            Full reference:
            <a href="/docs/api/audit/">/docs/api/audit/</a>.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="prose" aria-labelledby="disclosure">
          <h2 id="disclosure">Responsible Disclosure</h2>
          <p>
            Found a security issue? Email
            <a href="mailto:hello@inferbridge.dev?subject=Security%3A%20"
              >hello@inferbridge.dev</a
            > with <code>Security:</code> in the subject line.
          </p>
          <p>
            We aim to acknowledge reports within 48 hours. Please do not
            publicly disclose issues before we have had a chance to address
            them.
          </p>
        </section>
      </article>
    </Container>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Layout>

<style>
  .page {
    padding-block: 32px 96px;
    background-color: var(--gray-950);
    min-height: 100vh;
  }

  .masthead {
    margin-bottom: 32px;
  }

  .back {
    color: var(--gray-300);
    font-size: var(--fs-body-sm);
    transition: color var(--transition);
  }

  .back:hover {
    color: var(--accent-text);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .doc {
    max-width: var(--text-max);
  }

  .doc-header {
    margin-bottom: 48px;
    padding-block-end: 24px;
    border-block-end: 1px solid var(--gray-700);
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: 2.5rem;
    line-height: 1.2;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }

  .lede {
    color: var(--gray-300);
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    max-width: 640px;
  }

  .prose {
    color: var(--gray-100);
    font-size: var(--fs-body);
    line-height: var(--lh-body);
  }

  .prose h2 {
    font-size: 1.625rem;
    line-height: 1.3;
    margin-block: 40px 16px;
  }

  .prose p {
    margin-bottom: 24px;
  }

  .prose ul {
    margin-block: 0 24px;
    padding-inline-start: 28px;
  }

  .prose li {
    margin-block: 6px;
  }

  .prose code {
    background-color: var(--gray-800);
    padding: 2px 6px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--accent-text);
    font-size: 0.92em;
  }

  .prose a {
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-decoration-thickness: 1px;
    text-underline-offset: 3px;
  }

  .prose strong {
    color: var(--gray-50);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .prose em {
    font-style: italic;
  }
</style>
